commitResults.messageTitle: Update program to throw errors rather than return command result
commitResults.messageBody:
The commit changes involve throwing exceptions rather than catching them and returning command result. This is to introduce standardization and make it easier to spot any errors.

The commit also ammends test cases so that they all pass now.

commitResults.messageTitle: Handle exceptional cases that might occur while using the add command
commitResults.messageBody:
The program will specify which parameters are missing if an add command is incomplete.

The user is also now required to either include all or none of the policy variables when using the add command.

commitResults.messageTitle: Undergo more extensive error handling for add command
commitResults.messageBody:
Fixed the issue of preamble before prefix wrongly being detected as incomplete input.

Added more tests so that all exceptions for the add command are well tested.

commitResults.messageTitle: Make error messages more intuitive and adhere to OOP
commitResults.messageBody:
Collated all the error messages into one class for OOP.

Changed some of the error messages to make the error easier to detect, mainly the issue of preamble.

commitResults.messageTitle: Handle duplication that might occur in adding or editing
commitResults.messageBody:
Add and edit commands have been changed such that a new entry or an edit to an entry cannot use a policy number used by another code. This check should not occur for code with no policy.

The issue of 2 policies with the same name has also been ammended. Instead, addition or edits should work as long as all the fields are not the same. This is the only duplicate case.

Some of the test cases in EditCommandTest are yet to be handled.

The use of "sort" will be recognized as a command to arrange persons from closest expiring policy expiration date to latest.

Those with no specified policy are at the end of the database.

The persons are not auto sorted and thus everytime you run the sort command must be used again.
